sec-110/module-1-internet-history-and-st.title: Module 1 - Internet History and Statistics
sec-110/module-1-internet-history-and-st.description:
First iteration Arpanet in 1969
Eventually led to worldwide web administered by ICANN
First virus documented creeper, self replicating, non-malious
1968: Internet Engineering Task Force created
1990: Arpanet decommissioned, administration given to NSFNET
1991: World Wide Web introduced
1995: private sector takes over internet, NSFNET dissolved
3 policy areas
Online rights
Cybersec
Data privacy
Cyber-attack motives
Cyber crime Crypto
Money
Identify theft IP theft Software
Designs
Movies
music Espionage spying Terrorism Propaganda, diversions, etc Hacktivism Defacement, DoS, etc Messing around
Each incident in 2020 cost on average ½ million in damages
Majority of internet is underseas cabling
Data stored in large power hungry datacenters
Different countries have different views of network administration
US and Allies: open internet
China: closed internet with heavy controls in/out

sec-110/module-3-data-types-and-security.title: Module 3 - Data Types and Security
sec-110/module-3-data-types-and-security.description:
Bit-level data: storage, transfer, and bit-level operations of data (input/output, processing)
System-level data: roles and authorized resources to be used for reading, writing, and data processing
Personal-level data: SSN, username/passwords, address, biometrics, medical history, credit history, background checks, recordings, grades…
Policy-level data: Rules how to protect data on all the levels above. 
McCumber Cube
Security Goals 
Information States 
Countermeasures (security controls)
Data protection laws
HIPAA
CFAA
GDPR
CCPA

sec-110/module-5-cia-v2.html.title: Module 5 - CIA V2
sec-110/module-5-cia-v2.html.description:
Confidentiality: Using cryptography to keep data private
Integrity: Using cryptography to ensure that data has not been altered
Authentication: Verifying that user is who they claim
Non-repudiation: Ensure that user performed activity by proof that they cannot deny

sec-110/module-6-cryptography.html.title: Module 6 - Cryptography
sec-110/module-6-cryptography.html.description:
Non-Repudiation: Digital signatures, digital certificates.
Cryptographic Salt: add a string of random characters to a password before it is hashed and stored to create an extra layer of randomness.
Steganography is the practice of concealing information within another message or physical object to avoid detection.

info_showOrphanNodes.description: Show nodes that are not connected to any other nodes.

info_showAttachments.description: Show attachments like images and PDFs as nodes in the graph.

info_allowGlobalGraph.description: Allow the user to view the global graph of all nodes.

info_allowExpand.description: Allow the user to pop-out the graph view to take up the whole screen

info_attractionForce.description: How much should linked nodes attract each other? This will make the graph appear more clustered.

info_linkLength.description: How long should the links between nodes be? The shorter the links the more connected nodes will cluster together.

info_repulsionForce.description: How much should nodes repel each other? This will make disconnected parts more spread out.

info_centralForce.description: How much should nodes be attracted to the center? This will make the graph appear more dense and circular.

info_edgePruning.description: Edges with a length above this threshold will not be rendered, however they will still contribute to the simulation. This can help large tangled graphs look more organised. Hovering over a node will still display these links.

info_minNodeRadius.description: How small should the smallest nodes be? The smaller a node is the less it will attract other nodes.

info_maxNodeRadius.description: How large should the largest nodes be? Nodes are sized by how many links they have. The larger a node is the more it will attract other nodes. This can be used to create a good grouping around the most important nodes.
